Yes — you can make that info box fully **responsive** and still print cleanly with a few lightweight rules.  
Add these to the same stylesheet that holds your light/dark theme code:

```css
/* --- Responsive adjustments --- */

/* 1️⃣ Mobile first (default up to ~600 px width) */
.info-box {
  width: 100%;
  box-sizing: border-box;
  margin: 1em 0;
}
.info-box p {
  margin-top: 0.5em;
  margin-bottom: 0.5em;
}

/* 2️⃣ Tablets & small laptops */
@media (min-width: 600px) {
  .info-box {
    padding: 1.2em 1.6em;
    max-width: 700px;       /* keeps line length readable */
    margin-left: auto;
    margin-right: auto;
  }
}

/* 3️⃣ Desktop screens */
@media (min-width: 1000px) {
  .info-box {
    font-size: 1em;
    max-width: 900px;
  }
}

/* 4️⃣ Print version */
@media print {
  .info-box {
    background: #fff !important;      /* removes colored background */
    color: #000 !important;
    border-left: 2pt solid #000;
    padding: 0.8em 1em;
  }
  .info-box a {
    color: #000;
    text-decoration: underline;       /* keeps visible link targets */
  }
  .footer-note {
    color: #000;
  }
}
```

**Why this works**
- Uses a **mobile‑first** layout: 100 % width on phones, centered with limited width on larger screens to keep lines readable.  
- The **print query** strips color and keeps a clear left rule for tone when printed or exported as PDF.  
- Keeps font sizes consistent with the rest of your site while avoiding harmonic changes between devices.

With these additions, the info box remains legible and attractive on phones, tablets, large monitors, and printed documents—so a single embed covers all use cases.
